liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: Prime Minister Anthony Albanese commented on the Gaza hospital blast during a joint press conference with Fijian Prime Minister Sitiveni Rabuka, who is visiting Canberra. "We have seen a devastating loss of innocent life since the attacks on Israel by the terrorist group Hamas," Mr Albanese said. "The scenes from the explosion at a Gaza City hospital are deeply distressing and it is clear that there has been a devastating loss of life. "Every innocent life matters, whether it is Israeli or Palestinian. "Our thoughts are with those killed, those injured and their loved ones. The protection of civilian lives must come first, as the parliament said in its resolution that we carried on Monday, and respect for international humanitarian law is paramount. "We condemn any indiscriminate attacks and targeting of civilian infrastructure, including hospitals and Australia joins with others in calling for international law to always be upheld."
liveBlogPostPrepared.title: Anthony Albanese says 'every innocent life matters'

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: US President Joe Biden says he is "outraged" by the explosion at al-Ahli Arab Hospital and said he had directed his national security team to gather information about exactly what had happened. "I am outraged and deeply saddened by the explosion at the Al Ahli Arab hospital in Gaza, and the terrible loss of life that resulted," Biden, who is on his way to Israel, said in a statement. "The United States stands unequivocally for the protection of civilian life during conflict and we mourn the patients, medical staff and other innocents killed or wounded in this tragedy."

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: Foreign Minister Penny Wong says the government is planning an additional departure flight today for Australians trying to leave Tel Aviv for Dubai. A government assisted-departure flight landed in Sydney from Dubai last night, carrying 222 passengers, including 164 Australians. Meanwhile, 46 registered Australians remain in Gaza, with the Rafah border crossing with Egypt still closed. Senator Wong says the government is also supporting departure options for Australians in the West Bank, including working with partners to arrange transport to Jordan. She says more than 1,500 Australians have now left Israel and the Occupied Palestinian Territories.
liveBlogPostPrepared.title: Australian government planning another repatriation flight today

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: As soon as the news broke that Lachie Schultz wanted to get to Collingwood, immediately questions were being asked of Jack Ginnivan's future at the Pies. It looked like he was set to stick it out with the premiers, until late in the penultimate day of the trade period when it became clear that a switch to Hawthorn was on. Things have accelerated again this morning, with multiple reports confirming that Jack Ginnivan has requested a trade to the Hawks. Hawthorn's future second round pick is expected to be the fulcrum of the deal, with a bit of other shuffling, but this one is now absolutely and categorically on. Jack Ginnivan will become a Hawk today. Didn't think we'd be saying that this time yesterday.

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: Unions are calling on the Queensland government and Glencore to provide support to workers, after the company announced it will close its copper mines by 2025. At least 1,200 employees will be affected. Australian Workers' Union Queensland Secretary Stacey Schinnerl says it's a sad day for the entire Mount Isa community. "Now is the time for the government to cut through the green tape and fast track approvals for new mines in the region to provide a suitable transition for affected workers. We are calling on Glencore to provide redeployment opportunities to local workers who will be affected by these closures," she said. In a statement, Glencore's chief operating officer, Sam Strohmayr says studies revealed the remaining mineral resources were not economically viable due to low ore grades, a lack of safe extraction areas and ageing infrastructure. "The reality of mining is that mines have a beginning, middle and end. And unfortunately after 60 years of operation, Mount Isa's underground copper operations have now reached that end." He says the focus over the next few months will be to provide support to employees, contractors, suppliers and the Mount Isa community. "It's too early to put a figure on how many people may receive redundancies until we work through a process of speaking to each worker and discuss options around retention, redeployment, and retaining. Redundancies are the last resort and will be offered only when other options have been exhausted." The company says its other metal assets including the copper smelter, George Fisher mine, zinc-lead concentrator and lead smelter will all continue operating in Mount Isa.
liveBlogPostPrepared.title: Unions call for support after news of mine closures in Mount Isa

The ASX 200 is down -0.03% to 7,054 points and the broader All Ordinaries is down -0.02% to 7,243 points (at 12:25pm AEDT). The energy, healthcare and basic materials sectors are up, while the utilities and technology sectors are leading the losses. The big shock today has been Credit Corp Group's massive meltdown after it announced a write-down on its US ledger assets. It's currently d own -31% to $11.89. AMP shares touched a two-month low today, after it flagged lower growth expectations for the rest of the year. High interest rates are hurting the wealth manager's earnings. Shares dropped as much as 4.4% during the morning session and are currently -1.8% down. Southern Cross Media shares shot up almost 18% this morning after it received an unsolicited takeover bid from ARN Media and Anchorage. liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: ARN Media and Anchorage have launched an unsolicited takeover bid for Southern Cross Media. Under the proposal Southern Cross shareholders would receive 0.753 ARN shares and 29.6 cents cash per share. Southern Cross owns the Triple M and Hit radio stations. ARN says if the deal goes ahead, the radio and tv assets of both companies will be kept separate. CEO Ciaran Davis said the deal would create value for shareholders. "ARN is ideally positioned to support and operate an expanded regional radio network and as a combined group of scale in digital audio, positioned to compete efficiently and effectively with international competitors." Southern Cross Media recommends shareholders take no action at this stage. It says the board will consider the proposal. Shares were up 17.8% to 86 cents (at 12.05PM AEDT).
